{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8b94c433-c689-46fb-b670-59a1de47b6da","content":"No project found at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- Your MCP server must use **stdio transport** (not HTTP). If you're using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, ensure you call `.WithStdioServerTransport()` in your host builder.\n\n**If you publish your server** as a standalone executable instead, you can point directly to the binary:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot Chat panel in agent mode — VS Code will auto-discover and start the server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b8a9a7e6-5c98-4ecf-8235-33f868357fc8","outputTokens":356,"requestId":"842B:24244F:F78FCC:13885BF:69FFDAF2"},"id":"3f7c8170-b252-459a-abcd-1b4378f17981","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:10:19.237Z","parentId":"a54778f2-9e57-4e8d-9174-4b8e457773d1"}
